Plotting Roman Roads and Time

by jaro

17 August 2021

Roman roads network

This post concerns representation of ancient Roman roads in time with data from the article:

Fousek J, Kaše V, Mertel A, Výtvarová E, Chalupa A (2018) Spatial constraints on the diffusion of religious innovations: The case of early Christianity in the Roman Empire. PLoS ONE 13(12): e0208744. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0208744

Preliminaries

Load "multigraph" package and check its version. 
# load package and check version
library("multigraph")
packageVersion("multigraph")
[1] '0.95'

Dataset

In the previous post , the data of the Roman Empire transport network consisted on three files that were s007, s006, and s008 for edgelist with ancient cities travel costs, settlement labels with coordinates population estimates.

We work now with a dataset that is named ponet and which can be downloaded from GH

source(file="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/sdam-au/R_code/master/data/ponet.r")

The last variable of the second data frame in the structure of this data records years with evidence of christianity. As with population estimates, there is missing data in this attribute.

str(ponet)

With the latest version of function multigraph() this dataset or other dataset is automatically plotted as long as has an object component named net that contains and array or, as in this case, an edgelist having one or more kinds of relations.

Graph representation

The following plot has a force directed layout whose coordinates are recorded in object netcds obtained from GH

source(file="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/sdam-au/R_code/master/data/netcds.r")
# graph of network in 'ponet'
multigraph(ponet, directed=FALSE, coord=netcds)

However, many times is convenient to count with an object that records the adjacency matrix of the network, which in this case is valued rather than dichotomous.

min(ponet$net[ponet$net>0])
[1] 0.07349514

Valued adjacency matrix

# obtain matrix from send/receive/ties comma-separated-table
net <- multiplex::read.srt(ponet$net, header=TRUE, sep=",")

Dichotomous net from the minimum cost as the cut-off value.

#  minimum cost is in 'ponet'
net0 <- multiplex::dichot(net, c=min(ponet$net[ponet$net>0]))

We plot the dichotomized network with settlement labels rather than their ids and using the layout coordinates of the previous graph. Since ponet is an aggregated dataset of s007, s006, and s008, there are entries in the network attributes with missing labels. We omit these to plot the network.

# customize
scp <- list(directed=FALSE, pos=0, ecol=8, col=8, fsize=6)
multigraph(net0, coord=netcds, scope=scp, lbs=na.omit(ponet$attr$label))

Graph with ancient Roman roads

Choosing settlements

The entries with population estimates are meant to be large cities.

# network id labels
nlbs <- as.numeric(dimnames(net)[[1]])

# table with population estimates only 
popltbl <- ponet$attr[-(na.action(na.omit(ponet$attr$popest))),]
head(popltbl)

we choose the labels of these entries in table popltbl

# 2nd column has labels in population estimates
lbs0 <- as.vector(popltbl[match(nlbs, popltbl$id),2])
multigraph(net0, coord=netcds, scope=scp, lbs=lbs0)

Roman roads and large cities 

# 5th column has population estimates
popl <- as.vector(popltbl[match(nlbs, popltbl$id),5])
# last entries

multigraph(net*100, coord=netcds, scope=scp, lbs=lbs0, cex=popl, valued=TRUE)

Roman roads with large cities as valued graph

Time dimension

For time, we create another table that records christianity.

# Table with CHrist population only 
xtbl <- ponet$attr[-(na.action(na.omit(ponet$attr$christ))),]

Again, we need to deal with missing information.

Once we count with the settlements in each point of time, we proceed with the construction of their adjacency matrices.

# matrices
nett1 <- rel.sys(net0, type="toarray", sel=t1[,1])
nett2 <- rel.sys(net0, type="toarray", sel=t2[,1])
nett3 <- rel.sys(net0, type="toarray", sel=t3[,1])

Adding missing nodes

However, not all id entries in t1 to t3 are in the above matrices

t1[which(!(t1[,1]%in%dimnames(nett1)[[1]])),1]
[1] 50657
t2[which(!(t2[,1]%in%dimnames(nett2)[[1]])),1]
[1] 50479 50481 50503 50615
t3[which(!(t3[,1]%in%dimnames(nett3)[[1]])),1]
 [1] 50433 50477 50478 50484 50490 50616 50629 50659 50663 50668 50670 50675 50680 50685 50712

We can add the entries with argument 'add' from function transf() available in the "multiplex" package.

nett1a <- transf(nett1, type="toarray", add=t1[which(!(t1[,1]%in%dimnames(nett1)[[1]])),1])
nett2a <- transf(nett2, type="toarray", add=t2[which(!(t2[,1]%in%dimnames(nett2)[[1]])),1])
nett3a <- transf(nett3, type="toarray", add=t3[which(!(t3[,1]%in%dimnames(nett3)[[1]])),1])

Transport network

# labels
lbs1 <- as.vector(t1[match(nlbs, t1$id),2])
lbs2 <- as.vector(t2[match(nlbs, t2$id),2])
lbs3 <- as.vector(t3[match(nlbs, t3$id),2])

Clustering of nodes at the three points of time.

# clustering
ct1 <- ct2 <- ct3 <- vector(length=dim(net0)[1])
#
ct1[which(dimnames(net0)[[1]]%in%t1[,1])] <- 1
ct2[which(dimnames(net0)[[1]]%in%t2[,1])] <- 1
ct3[which(dimnames(net0)[[1]]%in%t3[,1])] <- 1
# another scope for time
scpt0 <- list(directed=FALSE, pos=0, ecol=8, fsize=7)
title <- expression(bolditalic('t'[1])*'  (100 AD)')
multigraph(net0, coord=netcds, scope=scpt0, clu=ct1, col=c("gray","blue"), lbs=lbs1, main=title)

Roman roads with christianity 100 AD 

title <- expression(bolditalic('t'[2])*'  (200 AD)')
multigraph(net0, coord=netcds, scope=scpt0, clu=ct2, col=c("gray","blue"), lbs=lbs2, main=title)

Roman roads with christianity 200 AD 

title <- expression(bolditalic('t'[3])*'  (304 AD)')
multigraph(net0, coord=netcds, scope=scpt0, clu=ct3, col=c("gray","blue"), lbs=lbs3, main=title)

Roman roads with christianity 304 AD

Cumulated

ct123 <- vector(length=dim(net0)[1])

ct123[which(dimnames(net0)[[1]]%in%t1[,1])] <- 1
ct123[which(dimnames(net0)[[1]]%in%t2[,1])] <- 2
ct123[which(dimnames(net0)[[1]]%in%t3[,1])] <- 3

We create the labels of settlements in the three points of time.

lbs123 <- as.vector(mapply(function(...) {tmp <- c(...); tmp[!is.na(tmp)][1]}, lbs1,lbs2,lbs3))

And plot with customized graph.

scptp <- list(pos=0, ecol=8, alpha=c(.8,.8), clu=ct123, col=c("gray","#6600FF","#6666FF","#66CCFF"), showLbs=F)
title <- expression(bolditalic('t'[1-3])*'  (100, 200, 304 AD)')
multigraph(net0, directed=FALSE, coord=netcds, scope=scptp, lbs=lbs123, main=title)

Roman roads with christianity 100-200-304 AD
